President Donald J. Trump has declared a major disaster in the State of South Carolina due to severe storms, tornadoes, and straight-line winds that occurred from April 12 to April 13, 2020. This declaration allows for Federal aid to supplement State, tribal, and local recovery efforts in the affected areas. Federal funding will be made available to individuals in the counties of Aiken, Colleton, Hampton, Marlboro, Oconee, Orangeburg, and Pickens, which can include grants for temporary housing and home repairs, low-cost loans for uninsured property losses, and other programs to help with recovery. Federal funding is also available for emergency work and the repair or replacement of facilities damaged in the counties of Barnwell, Colleton, Georgetown, Hampton, Oconee, Orangeburg, and Pickens. Additionally, Federal funding is available for statewide hazard mitigation measures. Allan Jarvis has been named the Federal Coordinating Officer for Federal recovery operations in the affected areas. Damage assessments are still ongoing, and more counties may be designated for assistance once assessments are completed. Residents and business owners in the designated counties can begin applying for assistance through the DisasterAssistance.gov website or by calling the toll-free numbers provided. The FEMA News Desk can be contacted for further information.